<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-740-188  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 740 188.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Oct 1989 v12 n10 p54(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Made in Japan. (Japanese competition in the global graphicshardware market)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kiely, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Japanese competitiveness in the global graphics systems market isincreasing.andP;  Japanese products already dominate the picture-tubemarket and areas that require graphics in the consumer-electronicsand video-games market.andP;  Industry analysts expect Japanese vendorsto push more sophisticated graphics tools, particularlyperipherals, in the worldwide markets in the next few years - asituation wherein some US computer graphics vendors will be hurtby the match-up against Japanese-style export strategies,marketing strategies, and higher-quality goods.andP;  In facing up toJapanese competition, industry insiders contend that US companiesare disadvantaged by cultural realities such as short-sightedbusiness values and an inability to focus on national, rather thancorporate, interests.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Japanese CompetitionGraphics SystemsMarket ShareImage ProcessingComputer-Aided DesignSemiconductor IndustryMarketing StrategyTechnologyManufacturersMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>